metadata.name: twofiftythousand #339
metadata.description:
twofiftythousand is about the chaos of unlimited decisions. Look for a pattern in the noise.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). metadata.name: Woolly #50
metadata.description:
Combining both CPU and GPU techniques to render a raymarched scene using a grid of lines according to the surface data from the shader output. 

* Variations:
- Number of balls
- Waves pattern
- Perspective
- Colors
- 10% chance of inverted version

CPU and GPU intensive

metadata.name: Waves and Ripples #52
metadata.description:
Waves and Ripples is an implementation of a continuous CA, where wave like behaviours are obtained from the influence of neighbour cells over the cell itself. Depeding on the connections config for each cell, different patterns will emerge, creating waves, ripples, or a mix of both. When single loop is on, the calculations and drawings are done at once, which makes for a more chaotic visual.
Best enjoyed in full-screen :) 

Click anywhere to restart

Features : 
  shrinkFactor : 3 types
  connectArray: 16 possibilities,
  extraConnection: 4 types,
  mutualNeighbour: 40% chance,
  singleLoop: 30% chance
  monoChromo:  15% chance

Inspired by Matt Pearson's book.

metadata.name: Agents 2.0 #25
metadata.description:
There are more than thousand agents(random). These agents can move in any direction. I have given 3 types of direction. First is single(together) direction, second is multi(against) direction and the last is "No Movement(Direction)". Agents have their  own speed, size, movement smoothness, and turbulence. The art is programmatically drawn using basic shapes, math, random using p5js.

All the agents walks around 100 to 230 steps. All speed, smoothness, waviness, turbulence, size, direction, color are randomly generated.

In this art, I am using 29 color palettes. these palettes are from: https://ronikaufman.github.io/color_pals/

Press s or 'S' to save image in default quality.
Add scale=print& before fxhash in the URL to save image in high quality.
Add scale=print2& before fxhash in the URL to save image in highest quality.

Example:
Before: https://gateway.fxhash2.xyz/ipfs/QmYiErKegzf66TgVB...../?fxhash=ooXFx4Cbn23Sacb...
After: https://gateway.fxhash2.xyz/ipfs/QmYiErKegzf66TgVB...../?scale=print&fxhash=ooXFx4Cbn23Sacb... 

Note: Art can take some minutes to render.

Art: 8/2/2022
Created By: ArtLife
Twitter: https://twitter.com/iamPraveenIN

metadata.name: PXL #48
metadata.description:
PXL is an exploration of video synthesis, each pixel containing 4 cells phasing between two values. This effect creates all sorts of interesting effects when scaled up, so enjoy the completely unique effect your optical illusion generates.

There is a 5% chance to generate a wave glitch in your pattern.

Color palettes:
80% Normal (Randomly Generated)
10% Monochrome
5% RGB
5% CMYK

Press 's' to save a png
Press 'm' to save a 10s mp4 (can take up to 2m to render)

metadata.name: Rebug #424
metadata.description:
A debug view of the underlying particulate algorithm of Atoms' Gaze and Quantum Folly. Refined as a gift for collectors.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-08-06 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: Phantoms #41
metadata.description:
Phantoms is a series of hazy memories of distant places. Some tranquil, others sinister, each scene is as much defined by what is revealed as by what remains unseen.

In this collection I aim to juxtapose hard and soft. Blocky shapes form the core of the compositions. Upon these surfaces, soft textures appear to flow and drip over the sides. Varying levels of opacity, lighting, and fog effects further soften the scenes to create an atmospheric, dream-like quality. By remaining semi-abstract, each of the color palettes are given the space to influence the mood dramatically.

metadata.name: Tesseract #483
metadata.description:
'Tesseract' is a generative collection drawing on the concept of the cube from oneirology, the interpretation of dreams. In many mythologies and fields of study, the square is considered a 'perfect shape', thus with its abstraction into three isometric dimensions, the cube is seen by some as a representation of the various aspects of the human condition.

In 'Tesseract', the ribbons flowing between the cubes represent the shared experiences that connect us all. No matter how different our lives might be, we all go through the same joys, sorrows, trials, tribulations and experience attachments of varying degrees. 

It is these experiences that bind us together and make us who we are. With these concepts in mind, viewers are invited to interpret each composition as it relates to them and their unique story, from the perspective of that which has been and that which is yet to be experienced.

Press 'S' to save a high resolution PNG at 2400 x 3396 px.

metadata.name: simple things #211
metadata.description:
Thereâ€™s beauty in simple things. Sunlight. A reflection on a puddle. The flight of a bird. Observing the clouds. Spending time with loved ones.

To celebrate the re-opening of fxhash, I'd like to contribute with some simple thing to enjoy among friends who rejoin after some time.

Simple things is a piece that is just that: simple things. Nothing fancy here. Simple circles doing simple movement, with simple colours. Maybe the viewer will rejoice in observing them transit on the screen.

It has some controls: you can press â€œsâ€ to save a png file. You can set a higher resolution pressing â€œdâ€ followed by 1-9 to increase pixel density (if you get a black image, press â€œd 0â€ and start again with a lower number). Simple controls.

It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).

The pieces exhibit simple variations: palettes, circle sizes, density of elements, backgrounds. The colours might be inverted sometimes. The direction of the movement changes also in some pieces. Some are grayscale pieces.

Just like in life, enjoying simple things is sometimes enough to leave behind the noise and our worries. Also like in life, if one wants something extra, they may get it by looking for it...

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-RodrÃ­guez, @msoriaro.
Made in p5.js, and glsl for the image controls.
